'''Lindy West''' (born March 9, 1982) is an American writer, comedian and activist. She is the author of the essay collection ''[[Shrill: Notes from a Loud Woman]]'' and a contributing opinion writer for ''[[The New York Times]]''. The topics she writes about include [[feminism]], [[popular culture]], and the [[fat acceptance movement]].<ref name=ContributingNYT/><ref name=Profile>[http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/lindy-west/Author?oid=21605 "Author Archive: Lindy West."] ''The Stranger.'' Accessed on January 21, 2012.</ref><ref name=Brodeur2013>{{Citation |last= Brodeur |date= July 7, 2013 |title= Lindy West: Finding 'Invisible Hypocrisies' |url = http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/lindy-west-finding-lsquoinvisible-hypocrisiesrsquo/ |newspaper= [[The Seattle Times]] |first= Nicole }}</ref><ref name=StrangerMasthead>{{Citation |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111101113125/http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Page?oid=21244 |url= http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Page?oid=21244  |archivedate= November 1, 2011 |newspaper= [[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |title= Masthead }}</ref>

==Career==
In 2009, West began working as the film editor for Seattle's alternative weekly newspaper, ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]''.<ref name=Profile/> In 2011, she moved to Los Angeles, but continued to write for ''The Stranger'' until September 2012.<ref name=Profile/><ref>[http://seattlest.com/2011/08/30/lindy_west_announces_move_to_la_sea.php "Lindy West Announces Move to LA, Seattle Cries."] ''Seattlest.'' August 30, 2011. Accessed on January 21, 2012.</ref><ref>West, Lindy. [http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/concessions/Content?oid=9935779 "So Long, Suckers!!! I Never Liked You!"] ''The Stranger''. September 13, 2011. Accessed on January 21, 2012.</ref>

She was a staff writer for [[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Waldman, Katy|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2012/08/03/stop_calling_yourself_a_feminist_.html|title=Stop Calling Yourself A Feminist|website=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|date=August 3, 2012|accessdate=August 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://articles.redeyechicago.com/2012-08-06/news/33086722_1_column-tosh-outrage "Whoa, The Reaction To That Column Was Crazy"] ''RedEye Chicago.'' Accessed on August 20, 2012.</ref> where she wrote on racism, [[sexism]], and [[sizeism|fat shaming]].<ref name=Brodeur2013/><ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.seattlemag.com/article/seattles-lindy-west-brings-womens-issues-light-online |title= Seattle's Lindy West Brings Women's Issues to Light Online; Writer, performer and activist Lindy West keeps her wit about her |first= Brangien |last= Davis  |date= January 2014 |magazine= Seattle Magazine }}</ref> West's work has been published in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/culture/author/lindywest1/|title=Lindy West|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate= January 21, 2012}}</ref> ''[[GQ]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/contributors/lindy-west|title=Contributors: Lindy West|work=[[GQ]] |accessdate=January 21, 2012}}</ref> the ''[[New York Daily News]]'',<ref>West, Lindy. [http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/anatomy-a-racist-awkward-relationship-mel-gibson-article-1.465097 "Anatomy of a racist: Our awkward relationship with Mel Gibson."] ''NY Daily News.'' July 19, 2010. Accessed on January 21, 2012.</ref> [[Vulture (blog)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture.com]],<ref>{{cite web |date= February 2, 2012 |title=Glee Recap: Takin' It to the Streets|first=Lindy|last=West|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/02/glee-recap-season-3-episode-11.html|publisher=[[Vulture.com]]}}</ref> [[Deadspin]], [[Cracked.com]],<ref>{{cite web|title=How To Be a Person: A Guide to Life for the Recent Graduate |date= June 11, 2011 |author= West, Lindy |url=http://www.cracked.com/article_19292_how-to-be-person-guide-to-life-recent-graduate.html |publisher=[[Cracked.com]] }}</ref> [[MSNBC]]<ref name="lindy west bio">{{cite web|title=I Jumped the Shark on My Pony. It Is My Pony's Only Trick. |url=http://lindywest.net/bio |publisher=Lindy West |accessdate=October 25, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203025/http://lindywest.net/bio |archivedate=October 29, 2013 |df= }}</ref> and ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=Profile /><ref>{{Citation |url= https://www.theguardian.com/profile/west-lindy |title= Lindy West [author profile] |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate= January 21, 2012 }}</ref> Describing West's often-comedic approach to serious issues, [[Dayna Tortorici]] wrote in ''The New York Times'' that West: <blockquote>has changed more minds this way than you could count. One of the most distinctive voices advancing feminist politics through humor, West is behind a handful of popular pieces — "How to Make a Rape Joke" on Jezebel, "Hello, I Am Fat" on The Stranger’s blog, "Ask Not for Whom the Bell Trolls; It Trolls for Thee" on "[[This American Life]]" — that have helped shift mainstream attitudes about [[body image]], comedy and online harassment over the past several years. Culture molds who we are, West argues, but it’s ours to remold in turn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/19/books/review/sex-object-a-memoir-and-shrill-notes-from-a-loud-woman.html|title=‘Sex Object: A Memoir’ and ‘Shrill: Notes From a Loud Woman’|last=Tortorici|first=Dayna|date=2016-06-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref></blockquote>In 2013 West won the [[Women's Media Center]] Social Media Award, which was presented by [[Jane Fonda]] in [[New York City]].<ref name="WomensMediaCenter">{{Citation|title=Lindy West Wins Women's Media Center Social Media Award|date=October 8, 2013|url=http://www.womensmediacenter.com/about/press/press-releases/lindy-west-wins-womens-media-center-social-media-award|publisher=[[Women's Media Center]]}}</ref> Accepting the award, West said, "I hear a lot these days about the lazy, aimless '[[millennials]]' – about how all we want to do is sit around twerking our iPods and Tweedling our Kardashians – and I also hear people asking, 'Where is the next generation of the social justice movement? Where are all the young feminists and womanists and activists?' Dude, they're on the internet."<ref name="WomensMediaCenter" /><ref>{{Cite AV media |medium=video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fR-t5MnOmuk|title= Lindy West Receives the WMC's Social Media Award from Jane Fonda }}</ref>

On September 19, 2015, West co-founded [[Shout Your Abortion]], a social media campaign on [[Twitter]] where people share their abortion experiences online without "sadness, shame or regret" for the purpose of "destigmatization, normalization, and putting an end to shame". The social media campaign was initiated in response to efforts by the [[United States House of Representatives]] to defund [[Planned Parenthood]] following the [[Planned Parenthood 2015 undercover videos controversy]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearson |first=Michael |title=Women embrace, criticize #ShoutYourAbortion|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/22/living/shout-your-abortion-feat/ |accessdate= October 12, 2015 |publisher=CNN |date= September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Buchanan|first1=Rose|title=Tens of thousands of women share their abortion experiences in global attempt to end stigma|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/tens-of-thousands-of-women-share-their-abortion-experiences-in-global-attempt-to-end-stigma-10512161.html |accessdate= October 12, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date= September 22, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wilmer |first=Henry |title=The women 'shouting' their abortions |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-34327404 |accessdate=October 12, 2015 |publisher=BBC |date= September 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last =Bowden |first =George |title=Planned Parenthood' #ShoutYourAbortion Sees Women Take To Social Media To Help Save Funding |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/09/22/shout-your-abortion-sees-women-take-to-social-media-to-help-save-planned-parenthood-funding_n_8174748.html |accessdate= October 13, 2015 |website=[[Huffington Post]] |date= September 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last =Kahn |first =Matie |title= The Dark Side of Hashtag Activism |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/news/a30714/shoutyourabortion-hashtag-activism-harrassment/ |accessdate= October 24, 2015 |magazine=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |date= September 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last =Roy |first =Aditi |title=How the #ShoutYourAbortion Hashtag Started and Sparked a New Movement |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/shoutyourabortion-hashtag-started-sparked-movement/story?id=34631955 |accessdate= October 23, 2015 |publisher=ABC News| date= October 23, 2015}}</ref>

In 2016, West won ''The Stranger''{{'}}s [[Stranger Genius Award|Genius Award in Literature]]<nowiki/> for her book ''[[Shrill: Notes from a Loud Woman]].''<ref>{{citation|title=The 2016 Stranger Genius Awards|newspaper=The Stranger|location=Seattle|date=September 14, 2016|p=17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.thestranger.com/genius-awards-2016/2016/09/14/24558300/lindy-west |newspaper=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |date=September 14, 2016 |title= Lindy West Winner of a Stranger Genius Award in Literature |first= Christopher |last= Frizzelle }}</ref>

On July 1, 2017, West became a contributing opinion writer for ''The New York Times'', after having written two op-ed columns for the ''Times'' in 2016.
<ref name=ContributingNYT/> She writes a weekly column on feminism and popular culture.<ref name=ContributingNYT/>

==Personal life==
Originally from [[Seattle, Washington]], West is the daughter of Ingrid, who is a nurse, and Paul West, who was a musician.<ref name=ST/> She attended [[Occidental College]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref name=Profile/><ref name=PaulWestObit/>

On July 11, 2015, West married musician and writer [[Ahamefule J. Oluo]], younger brother of Seattle writer [[Ijeoma Oluo]].<ref name=CA>{{cite web|work=CityArts|url=http://www.cityartsonline.com/articles/qa-ahamefule-j-oluo|title=Q&A with Ahamefule J. Oluo |date= December 2, 2014 |first=Brett |last=Hamil}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Lindy |title=My wedding was perfect – and I was fat as hell the whole time|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/jul/21/my-wedding-perfect-fat-woman |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Ahamefule2011>{{Citation |title= My Father Is an African Immigrant and My Mother Is a White Girl from Kansas and I Am Not the President of the United States; Or, How to Disappoint Your Absent Father in 20 Words or Less |url= https://www.thestranger.com/seattle/my-father-is-an-african-immigrant-and-my-mother-is-a-white-girl-from-kansas-and-i-am-not-the-president-of-the-united-states/Content?oid=8932130  |first=Ahamefule J. |last= Oluo |newspaper=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |date=July 6, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=West2017>{{Citation |title= Roxane Gay: 'If I was conventionally hot and had a slammin' body, I would be president'  |first=Lindy |last=West |authorlink=Lindy West  |url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2017/jul/03/roxane-gay-lindy-west-if-i-was-conventionally-hot-i-would-be-president |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= July 3, 2017}}</ref>

